#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
partty — xargs-style parallel runner with split, in-place output.

Usage:
    partty [-P PROCS] [-n NARGS | -L MAX_LINES] [-I REPL] [--] CMD [ARGS...]

Reads items from stdin (whitespace-separated, like xargs default) and
runs up to PROCS invocations of CMD in parallel. The terminal is split
vertically into PROCS panes; each pane shows the live tail of one slot,
with a `+ <command>` header. As a slot finishes, the next queued item
takes over that pane.

When stdout is NOT a tty (pipes, CI, non-interactive shells), partty
falls back to a plain parallel runner — no pane UI: each invocation runs
with its combined stdout+stderr captured, and when it finishes its output
is printed as one labeled block (`+ <command>` … `[exit N]`). Blocks are
grouped per job (not line-interleaved) so parallel output stays readable.
Exit code is still the max of all children.

Options:
    -P PROCS         Max parallelism (default: os.cpu_count() or 4)
    -n NARGS         Items per invocation (default: 1). Ignored when -I is set.
    -L MAX_LINES     Use at most MAX_LINES nonblank input lines per command
                     invocation (xargs -L semantics). Trailing whitespace on
                     an input line continues it onto the next physical line
                     as one logical line. Each logical line's tokens become
                     args. Conflicts with -n and -I.
    -I REPL          Substitution mode: replace REPL in any of ARGS with the
                     current item. Forces NARGS=1.
    -S, --strip-ansi Strip ALL ANSI escapes from command output before
                     display. By default, SGR (color/style) escapes are
                     preserved and other escapes (cursor moves, screen
                     clears, OSC) are filtered out so they can't move the
                     cursor outside the pane.

Examples:
    ls *.tar.gz | partty -P8 gzip -dk
    find . -name '*.py' | partty -P4 -I{} python -m py_compile {}
    seq 1 20 | partty -P5 sleep
    ls -l | partty -L1 -P14 echo

Display:
- Each pane is backed by a small VT100-ish screen emulator. ANSI cursor
  moves (CUU/CUD/CUF/CUB, CUP, ED, EL, IL/DL, ICH/DCH/ECH, scroll up/down,
  save/restore cursor, SGR) update the screen buffer instead of bleeding
  out of the pane. Output that would move past the bottom row scrolls
  the screen up by one row; everything else is clamped to the pane size.
- SGR (color/style) is rendered with the cell's attributes intact. Pass
  --strip-ansi to render the screen as plain text without colors.
- Each child sees its pty size set to the pane size via TIOCSWINSZ, and
  the `LINES` / `COLUMNS` env vars are exported to match — so commands
  that read either source format to the pane width.
- SIGWINCH relayouts the block, resizes each pane's emulator, and pushes
  the new size to every child via TIOCSWINSZ (children re-read LINES /
  COLUMNS only if they handle SIGWINCH themselves).
- Final exit code is the max of all child exit codes.
"""

